 Supplementary Material 3: Detailed Description of Data Processing and Splitting Strategy
====================================================================
## 1. Data Source and Basic Information
- Data source: Investing.com, U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA)
- Target variable: Natural Gas Continuous Futures (NG1)
- Feature variables: 17 auxiliary variables (see Table 1 for classification)
- Time span: January 1, 2014 – January 22, 2024
- Total trading days: 2,651

## 2. Data Preprocessing Steps

### 2.1 Missing Value Handling
- Method: Linear interpolation
- Applied to all 18 variables (1 target + 17 features)
- Missing value ratio: <2% for each variable
- Special handling: For missing values at the beginning or end of the series, nearest neighbor imputation is used

### 2.2 Data Standardization
- Method: Min-Max normalization
- Formula: X_norm = (X - X_min) / (X_max - X_min)
- Key principle: Minimum and maximum values are computed only on the training set
- Avoiding data leakage: Validation and test sets are transformed using training set parameters
- Normalized range: [0, 1]

## 3. Chronological Data Splitting Strategy

### 3.1 Splitting Principles
- Maintain strict chronological order to prevent any future information leakage
- No random shuffling is performed
- Train/validation/test splits:
    - Training set: January 1, 2014 – December 31, 2019 (~70% of total data)
    - Test set: January 1, 2020 – January 22, 2024 (~30% of total data)
    - Validation set: The last 10% of the training set is used for early stopping and hyperparameter tuning

### 3.2 Sample Construction
- Sliding window approach:
    - Input sequence length (seq_len): 30 trading days
    - Prediction horizon (pred_len): 1 day (for single-step) or multiple days for multi-step forecasting
    - Step size: 1 day (moving the window forward by 1 day)
- Each sample:
    - X: normalized feature matrix of seq_len days
    - y: target value(s) corresponding to the prediction horizon
- Optional: Exponential time decay weights applied to past observations to emphasize recent data

### 3.3 Random Seed and Repetition
- Random seed: 42 (ensures reproducibility of model initialization and training)
- Number of repetitions: 10 (average results reported to reduce stochastic variability)


## 4. Multi-step Forecasting
- The model supports multi-step prediction by setting pred_len > 1
- For each input sequence of seq_len days, the target sequence consists of pred_len consecutive future values
- Sliding window is applied in the same manner to construct multi-step samples
